AR 1460":"30 March 1460","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1405":"1405","Louvois, 40 Rue Louvois, Vélizy-Villacoublay, Île-de-France, Francja":"Vélizy-Villacoublay, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France","Francois, Plaquemines, France":"France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Yiddish <i>ber</i> ‘bear’, probably influenced by the early medieval European practice of giving animal names to people. It is often paired with   Dov   in order to provide a Hebrew name in certain rituals."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Ier De Sarrebruck-Commercy was born in 1400, in France, his father, Aimé De Sarrebruck, was 30 and his mother, Dame de Louvais Marie de Chateauvillain, was 35. He had at least 1 daughter with Jeanne De Roucy Pierrepont. He died on 30 March 1460, in Vélizy-Villacoublay, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1400–30 MAR 1460":"1400–30. märts 1460","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1405–1459":"1405–1459","1436–1492":"1436–1492","1370–1414":"1370–1414","1365–1423":"1365–1423","1459":"1459","1414":"1414","1436":"1436","1423":"1423","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","1460":"1460","30 MAR 1460":"30. märts 1460","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1405":"1405","Louvois, 40 Rue Louvois, Vélizy-Villacoublay, Île-de-France, Francja":"Vélizy-Villacoublay, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Francois, Plaquemines, France":"Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1400–30 MAR 1460":"1400–30. maaliskuuta 1460","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1405–1459":"1405–1459","1436–1492":"1436–1492","1370–1414":"1370–1414","1365–1423":"1365–1423","1459":"1459","1414":"1414","1436":"1436","1423":"1423","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","1460":"1460","30 MAR 1460":"30. maaliskuuta 1460","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1405":"1405","Louvois, 40 Rue Louvois, Vélizy-Villacoublay, Île-de-France, Francja":"Vélizy-Villacoublay, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Ranska","Francois, Plaquemines, France":"Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1400–30 MAR 1460":"1400–30 mars 1460","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1405–1459":"1405–1459","1436–1492":"1436–1492","1370–1414":"1370–1414","1365–1423":"1365–1423","1459":"1459","1414":"1414","1436":"1436","1423":"1423","1400":"1400","1365":"13